WEBVTT

1
00:00:00.080 --> 00:00:00.720
Good afternoon.

2
00:00:02.020 --> 00:00:05.840
I hope everyone is enjoying this extraordinary annual meeting here in San Diego.

3
00:00:06.520 --> 00:00:10.500
I'm Dr. David Kirsch, a senior scientist at University Health Network's Princess

4
00:00:10.620 --> 00:00:11.600
Margaret Cancer Centre.

5
00:00:12.480 --> 00:00:16.320
It is my privilege to serve as chair of this year's selection committee for

6
00:00:16.360 --> 00:00:20.060
the AACR Award for the Lifetime Achievement in Cancer Research.

7
00:00:20.660 --> 00:00:23.480
The AACR established this prestigious award in

8
00:00:23.640 --> 00:00:27.300
2004 to honor individuals who have made significant

9
00:00:27.940 --> 00:00:31.640
and fundamental contributions in cancer research, who've had a

10
00:00:31.720 --> 00:00:35.700
lasting impact on the field, and have demonstrated a lifetime commitment to

11
00:00:35.740 --> 00:00:39.600
progress against cancer. This year's honoree is a scientist whose

12
00:00:39.640 --> 00:00:43.360
work has fundamentally transformed cancer research and profoundly

13
00:00:43.400 --> 00:00:46.520
impacted our field and cancer patients we serve.

14
00:00:47.400 --> 00:00:51.100
The 2026 AACR Award for Lifetime Achievement in Cancer

15
00:00:51.160 --> 00:00:53.440
Research is being awarded to Dr. James P.

16
00:00:53.520 --> 00:00:57.200
Allison of the University of Texas MD Anderson Cancer Center.

17
00:00:57.700 --> 00:01:01.300
Dr. Allison's discovery and development of immune checkpoint blockade

18
00:01:01.310 --> 00:01:05.240
therapy revolutionized cancer immunotherapy and reshaped

19
00:01:05.250 --> 00:01:07.860
the clinical landscape across many cancer types.

20
00:01:08.440 --> 00:01:12.240
Early in his career, Dr. Allison focused on understanding the fundamental

21
00:01:12.320 --> 00:01:15.360
biology of T cell activation and regulation.

22
00:01:15.800 --> 00:01:19.180
His laboratory identified key components of the T cell response,

23
00:01:19.550 --> 00:01:23.420
including the T cell receptor, which recognizes antigens presented

24
00:01:23.440 --> 00:01:26.730
by MHC molecules, and CD28, a critical

25
00:01:26.840 --> 00:01:30.160
co-stimulatory receptor required for full T cell

26
00:01:30.220 --> 00:01:32.710
activation. In the mid-1990s, Dr.

27
00:01:32.960 --> 00:01:36.760
Allison made a landmark discovery by demonstrating that CTLA-4

28
00:01:36.800 --> 00:01:40.520
functions as a negative regulator of T cell activation, a

29
00:01:40.560 --> 00:01:42.000
brake on the immune response.

30
00:01:42.940 --> 00:01:46.390
At a time when most efforts in immunotherapy focused on

31
00:01:46.500 --> 00:01:48.300
stimulating the immune system, Dr.

32
00:01:48.520 --> 00:01:52.380
Allison proposed a bold and unconventional idea that blocking

33
00:01:52.420 --> 00:01:55.720
inhibitory pathways could unleash antitumor immunity.

34
00:01:56.440 --> 00:02:00.280
His laboratory tested this hypothesis in preclinical models,

35
00:02:00.650 --> 00:02:04.060
showing that inhibition of CTLA-4 led to complete tumor

36
00:02:04.120 --> 00:02:08.021
rejection. This work laid the foundation for a new therapeutic

37
00:02:08.060 --> 00:02:12.000
paradigm, immune checkpoint blockade, a term coined by Dr. Allison.

38
00:02:12.600 --> 00:02:15.920
Translating this concept into the clinic required extraordinary

39
00:02:16.000 --> 00:02:19.769
persistence and vision, particularly in the face of skepticism and

40
00:02:19.880 --> 00:02:21.520
prior failures in immunotherapy.

41
00:02:22.060 --> 00:02:25.900
Ultimately, this work led to the development of the anti-CTLA-4

42
00:02:25.960 --> 00:02:29.860
antibody ipilimumab, which in 2011 became the first immune

43
00:02:29.880 --> 00:02:33.760
checkpoint inhibitor approved by the FDA after demonstrating a

44
00:02:33.780 --> 00:02:36.520
survival benefit in patients with metastatic melanoma.

45
00:02:37.140 --> 00:02:40.860
Notably, a subset of these patients experienced long-term, durable

46
00:02:40.920 --> 00:02:43.540
remissions lasting more than a decade. Dr.

47
00:02:43.600 --> 00:02:47.080
Allison's discovery catalyzed the development of an entirely new class

48
00:02:47.180 --> 00:02:50.970
of cancer therapies, including inhibitors targeting

49
00:02:51.000 --> 00:02:54.800
PD-1, PD-L1 pathway. Today, immune checkpoint blockade

50
00:02:54.840 --> 00:02:58.560
therapies are approved across numerous cancer types and have provided

51
00:02:58.600 --> 00:03:02.260
lasting benefit with improved survival to hundreds of thousands of patients

52
00:03:02.340 --> 00:03:06.210
worldwide. Importantly, Dr. Allison's work established a new principle in

53
00:03:06.240 --> 00:03:10.100
oncology that targeting the immune system, rather than the tumor alone, can

54
00:03:10.120 --> 00:03:13.980
produce durable and potentially curative responses.

55
00:03:14.400 --> 00:03:17.760
This paradigm shift continues to guide the development of next-generation

56
00:03:17.840 --> 00:03:21.200
immunotherapies and combination strategies. Dr.

57
00:03:21.460 --> 00:03:25.220
Allison remains at the forefront of cancer research, leading efforts to understand

58
00:03:25.280 --> 00:03:29.100
mechanisms of response and resistance to immunotherapy and to expand

59
00:03:29.140 --> 00:03:32.860
its benefits to more patients. He currently leads the James P.

60
00:03:32.980 --> 00:03:36.820
Allison Institute at the University of Texas MD Anderson

61
00:03:36.920 --> 00:03:39.750
Cancer Center. Among his many honorees, Dr.

62
00:03:39.940 --> 00:03:43.920
Allison was awarded the Nobel Prize in Physiology or Medicine in 2018

63
00:03:43.960 --> 00:03:47.700
for his groundbreaking discoveries in cancer immunotherapy. The impact of Dr.

64
00:03:47.960 --> 00:03:51.400
Allison's work is profound. His insights into immune

65
00:03:51.460 --> 00:03:55.340
regulation and his relentless commitment to translating discovery into therapy

66
00:03:55.380 --> 00:03:59.260
have saved and extended countless lives and continue to shape the future of

67
00:03:59.300 --> 00:04:02.780
cancer treatment. It's my great honor to introduce the 2026

68
00:04:02.820 --> 00:04:06.420
recipient of the AACR Award for Lifetime Achievement in Cancer Research,

69
00:04:06.800 --> 00:04:08.080
Dr. James Allison.

70
00:04:14.980 --> 00:04:17.260
Thank you, Dr. Kirsch, for that wonderful introduction.

71
00:04:18.459 --> 00:04:20.780
I'm glad to find all you guys, actually.

72
00:04:20.800 --> 00:04:24.320
I was sitting in a smaller room for a little while thinking this was it, and there

73
00:04:24.340 --> 00:04:27.460
was almost nobody in there. And I thought, "Well, at least my friends ought to

74
00:04:27.480 --> 00:04:31.320
come." But I discovered I was sitting in 6D or something then.

75
00:04:32.400 --> 00:04:35.140
Anyway, I'm here and glad to see all of you.

76
00:04:35.340 --> 00:04:38.630
And today, I would like to just talk a little bit about

77
00:04:39.460 --> 00:04:43.400
the background of checkpoint blockade, but more about some recent

78
00:04:43.440 --> 00:04:47.180
work that we've been doing, about some details of the mechanism,

79
00:04:48.320 --> 00:04:50.760
that are kind of interesting. I'm not going to give you too much

80
00:04:52.120 --> 00:04:54.140
up-to-date stuff on the clinical things.

81
00:04:54.300 --> 00:04:57.400
Just in the time permitted, I can just talk about the

82
00:04:58.520 --> 00:05:00.760
new mechanistic stuff that we got.

83
00:05:01.320 --> 00:05:05.260
Anyway, here are my disclosures. Don't invest in many of

84
00:05:05.300 --> 00:05:08.640
these companies. Most of them are underwater now anyway, because everything's

85
00:05:09.480 --> 00:05:12.960
down. I say that because one time somebody photographed my

86
00:05:13.680 --> 00:05:17.630
disclosure slide and published it in a magazine saying, "This is what

87
00:05:17.740 --> 00:05:19.600
you all are..." Anyway, don't do that.

88
00:05:20.860 --> 00:05:22.450
Anyway. Well, why immunotherapy?

89
00:05:22.560 --> 00:05:26.180
Well, this is an old slide, but I'll show it again because it sort of

90
00:05:26.300 --> 00:05:30.140
started these things off, and that's because of what cancer is.

91
00:05:30.180 --> 00:05:32.940
Cancer is a disease with lots of mutations, as we all know.

92
00:05:33.740 --> 00:05:36.980
And it's many different diseases if you look at it that way, each of which is

93
00:05:37.020 --> 00:05:40.440
caused by a different driver, and that's how you design therapies.

94
00:05:40.460 --> 00:05:44.200
But what people have found in the last years is that targeting single mutations

95
00:05:44.220 --> 00:05:48.200
doesn't work, partially because there's always another driver in the population,

96
00:05:48.240 --> 00:05:50.700
and that one will just take over when you kill all the first ones.

97
00:05:50.760 --> 00:05:50.920
So,

98
00:05:51.920 --> 00:05:55.460
it's hard to see how that's going to be really curative.

99
00:05:55.510 --> 00:05:59.500
It's been calculated there are 14 different ways a melanoma cell

100
00:05:59.540 --> 00:06:00.719
can escape

101
00:06:01.520 --> 00:06:04.700
the perfect BRAF

102
00:06:04.760 --> 00:06:08.600
inhibitor.By using other pathways, et cetera.

103
00:06:09.000 --> 00:06:12.540
So it's kind of hard to think how you could put 14 different things together in a

104
00:06:12.600 --> 00:06:16.460
therapy. Any event, immunotherapy's been disregarded for a

105
00:06:16.500 --> 00:06:20.360
long time because it had a lot of problems working, but theoretically it

106
00:06:20.440 --> 00:06:22.400
ought to work. One is specificity.

107
00:06:22.420 --> 00:06:26.120
What we know now, and suspected for a long time, is the target

108
00:06:26.240 --> 00:06:29.600
of T cells in immune response isn't to the tumor

109
00:06:30.820 --> 00:06:34.570
antigens you've read about in the class book, in the textbook so much as it is

110
00:06:34.980 --> 00:06:37.040
those that are produced by these mutations.

111
00:06:37.070 --> 00:06:40.900
And not just the drivers that the tumor biologists are interested in, but

112
00:06:40.980 --> 00:06:44.600
also the passengers of our immune system can see those as well.

113
00:06:44.680 --> 00:06:48.320
Anything that changes an amino acid that's expressed

114
00:06:48.380 --> 00:06:51.960
and fits the MHC of the patient can be an antigen, whether it's a

115
00:06:52.100 --> 00:06:54.740
driver or not. The immune system doesn't care.

116
00:06:54.790 --> 00:06:58.750
And once you've got T cells that could see it, they give rise to memory cells,

117
00:06:58.800 --> 00:07:02.170
of course, so potentially you've got those cells for the rest of your life that

118
00:07:02.200 --> 00:07:06.040
could come back. And if the tumor changes, you can easily just poke around

119
00:07:06.080 --> 00:07:09.820
with it again and get the immune system, which is a living thing itself, to

120
00:07:09.880 --> 00:07:13.710
adapt to that and change to it. So that's just another way of saying it's

121
00:07:13.740 --> 00:07:17.080
been clear for a long time that the immune system's a match for cancer,

122
00:07:17.900 --> 00:07:18.460
but

123
00:07:19.280 --> 00:07:23.100
let's just go ahead and try. So I thought it'd be a good idea to figure out really

124
00:07:23.120 --> 00:07:26.100
in detail how T cells work when I started all this.

125
00:07:26.180 --> 00:07:29.780
So we know now that there's signal one, which is the T cell antigen receptor.

126
00:07:29.820 --> 00:07:33.100
That's not enough. You need another costimulatory signal, which is

127
00:07:33.170 --> 00:07:37.100
CD28. Only when a T cell gets all that signal

128
00:07:37.540 --> 00:07:41.360
does it really turn on and start to divide

129
00:07:42.280 --> 00:07:46.110
by turning on these cell cycle things and making growth factors and then

130
00:07:46.120 --> 00:07:50.100
proliferate. Because you've got to grow that minority of cells into an army

131
00:07:50.140 --> 00:07:53.880
to kill the tumors. So that's the key expansion phase that has to

132
00:07:54.400 --> 00:07:56.740
occur very fast to get rid of tumors.

133
00:07:56.880 --> 00:08:00.740
But CTLA-4 comes along. It's turned on when you turn on CTLA-4,

134
00:08:01.240 --> 00:08:05.180
and after a while, CTLA-4 accumulates, and we think it gets

135
00:08:05.240 --> 00:08:09.180
to a point it's got about a three-log advantage over CD28

136
00:08:09.220 --> 00:08:11.700
in binding the ligand. So it outcompetes CD28.

137
00:08:11.760 --> 00:08:15.680
It turns off costimulation, and the cells gradually

138
00:08:15.740 --> 00:08:19.600
come to a stop. And so the idea I had was that, well, maybe the tumor

139
00:08:19.660 --> 00:08:23.060
cells are really, they're

140
00:08:23.140 --> 00:08:27.080
antigenic, but maybe they

141
00:08:27.120 --> 00:08:28.840
can't give the costimulatory signal.

142
00:08:29.020 --> 00:08:32.461
And sure enough, we showed that was the case, and they can't behave like an

143
00:08:32.500 --> 00:08:34.140
antigen-presenting cell as you see here.

144
00:08:34.670 --> 00:08:38.500
This is a T cell with CD28. You can see it fusing in the

145
00:08:38.560 --> 00:08:42.500
membrane. It's a GFP fusion as the T cell contacts the,

146
00:08:42.520 --> 00:08:44.620
in this case, antigen-presenting cell.

147
00:08:45.660 --> 00:08:47.700
But after that, the CTLA-4 comes around.

148
00:08:47.740 --> 00:08:51.180
It's in vesicles at the back of the cell, and it's drug then to the

149
00:08:51.220 --> 00:08:54.760
synapse, and actually, the molecules seem to be sprayed into the synapse.

150
00:08:55.240 --> 00:08:56.940
And there they could form because it's a

151
00:08:58.140 --> 00:08:58.640
multimeric

152
00:08:59.440 --> 00:09:01.920
binding of B7-1, which is also multimeric.

153
00:09:01.960 --> 00:09:05.560
You get a really high avidity thing, which just pushes CD28

154
00:09:06.200 --> 00:09:08.220
out of the synapse. So that's how it works.

155
00:09:08.980 --> 00:09:12.780
But anyway, the way it works in cancer is that tumor cells can't give

156
00:09:12.820 --> 00:09:15.280
those second signals, at least most solid tumors.

157
00:09:15.610 --> 00:09:19.120
At least no solid tumor can because they don't have the B7

158
00:09:19.180 --> 00:09:23.160
molecule. We showed that when the B7 was identified as

159
00:09:23.220 --> 00:09:26.680
the common ligand for both CD28 and CTLA-4.

160
00:09:27.220 --> 00:09:31.110
We put B7 into a number of tumors, and they won't even grow in mice because

161
00:09:31.160 --> 00:09:34.960
they elicit an immediate immune response, whether they were considered really

162
00:09:35.000 --> 00:09:37.480
poorly immunogenic or highly immunogenic.

163
00:09:37.900 --> 00:09:39.720
So the problem isn't they lack antigens.

164
00:09:39.760 --> 00:09:42.600
The problem is they can't initiate an immune response.

165
00:09:43.160 --> 00:09:46.920
So the idea that gave rise to checkpoints blockade is that the tumor gets a

166
00:09:46.960 --> 00:09:50.820
head start. You try to generate T cells, but CTLA-4 turns them

167
00:09:50.920 --> 00:09:54.160
off before you can get enough. So all we need to do is turn

168
00:09:54.200 --> 00:09:57.720
CTLA-4 off, and we can get tumors to

169
00:09:57.760 --> 00:10:01.720
grow. So this is one of the lot of experiments we did to

170
00:10:01.760 --> 00:10:02.720
prove that this is the case.

171
00:10:05.960 --> 00:10:09.860
Dana Leach and Max Krummel specifically did this experiment

172
00:10:09.920 --> 00:10:13.700
showing that if you inject a mouse with a tumor and it grows, if you inject

173
00:10:13.740 --> 00:10:17.210
an antibody to CD28 and block it, the tumor grows faster,

174
00:10:17.760 --> 00:10:21.710
showing there is a nascent immune response there, but it just can't get

175
00:10:21.759 --> 00:10:25.720
it done. But if you inject anti-CTLA-4, those tumors

176
00:10:25.780 --> 00:10:29.600
grow for a while and then get rejected. And those mice are permanently immune.

177
00:10:30.200 --> 00:10:32.280
The mice will never take that tumor again.

178
00:10:32.700 --> 00:10:36.340
We've tried that with many different tumor lines of mice, and it

179
00:10:36.460 --> 00:10:40.160
always worked, either by itself or with a vaccine or a little bit of

180
00:10:40.280 --> 00:10:43.860
chemo or something. But this was really a powerful way of allowing T

181
00:10:43.980 --> 00:10:45.500
cells to

182
00:10:47.100 --> 00:10:50.760
attack cancer. So with a lot of

183
00:10:50.800 --> 00:10:53.960
help from friends and others, we made the ipilimumab

184
00:10:54.700 --> 00:10:57.390
antibody, initially called MDX-010.

185
00:10:58.420 --> 00:10:59.680
And even it went in about

186
00:11:00.600 --> 00:11:03.420
2000 or so. It went into clinical trials first.

187
00:11:03.480 --> 00:11:03.620
It's

188
00:11:04.700 --> 00:11:08.420
early trials in other kinds of cancer, but finally focused in melanoma.

189
00:11:08.460 --> 00:11:12.380
And in the Phase I in melanoma, there were, I think, 3 out of 14 patients

190
00:11:12.420 --> 00:11:16.380
that had CRs. So it really got everybody's attention and

191
00:11:16.440 --> 00:11:17.840
led to the Phase III trial.

192
00:11:18.840 --> 00:11:20.920
Sharon Belvin here was one of the early

193
00:11:21.960 --> 00:11:25.640
participants in the Phase III trial that Jedd Wolchok ran at Sloan

194
00:11:25.660 --> 00:11:27.400
Kettering. She was diagnosed in

195
00:11:28.040 --> 00:11:31.560
2015. '14 and '15.

196
00:11:32.380 --> 00:11:33.360
She was being treated for

197
00:11:34.180 --> 00:11:37.900
metastatic melanoma. It had completely

198
00:11:38.080 --> 00:11:41.740
gotten in her lungs. She couldn't breathe well. That was how she presented.

199
00:11:42.260 --> 00:11:44.839
She had 31 mets in her lungs, as you can see here.

200
00:11:45.220 --> 00:11:48.820
Her liver was also completely riddled with too many to count,

201
00:11:49.160 --> 00:11:51.960
and she had a centimeter-and-a-half brain tumor, as it turned out.

202
00:11:52.040 --> 00:11:55.880
She had two rounds of chemotherapy, a round of radiation to no effect,

203
00:11:56.300 --> 00:11:59.660
and then Jedd told her she had the choice of hospice or

204
00:11:59.700 --> 00:12:02.500
CTLA-4. She got a treatment with CTLA-4.

205
00:12:02.600 --> 00:12:05.440
Within a few months, her tumors were just completely gone.

206
00:12:05.480 --> 00:12:06.880
When she came back for a checkup,

207
00:12:07.860 --> 00:12:11.620
there was a lot of confusion because they couldn't find any sign that she had

208
00:12:11.680 --> 00:12:15.160
cancer on any of her films, on any of the diagnostic stuff.

209
00:12:15.180 --> 00:12:18.840
And so the radiologist at first thought that they'd been mixed up or something, but

210
00:12:18.860 --> 00:12:22.100
it turned out it hadn't. Anyway, so she went on to a CR.

211
00:12:22.780 --> 00:12:26.552
There are her two kids in 2016, and I saw herThis

212
00:12:26.612 --> 00:12:29.302
summer early, and those two kids are about ready to go to college.

213
00:12:29.852 --> 00:12:33.812
Everybody's still fine, and she's had no reason for relapse, no reason for

214
00:12:33.852 --> 00:12:37.732
any treatments or anything in 21 years now since she got

215
00:12:37.772 --> 00:12:41.632
it. So she's one of the most-- There were earlier survivals from some of the

216
00:12:41.652 --> 00:12:45.292
other smaller trials, but the earliest from that phase from that

217
00:12:45.612 --> 00:12:49.492
trial that Jed did. Anyway, when the trial finished, there were about 20% of

218
00:12:49.552 --> 00:12:53.212
the patients that were alive, and that was extended for 10

219
00:12:53.252 --> 00:12:56.592
years. About 20% of patients with melanoma

220
00:12:57.112 --> 00:12:57.952
were alive

221
00:12:58.792 --> 00:13:02.512
10 years after treatment with ipilimumab, which is pretty

222
00:13:02.712 --> 00:13:05.932
significant considering that when we started this trial, the

223
00:13:06.372 --> 00:13:10.312
median survival was seven months, six to

224
00:13:10.392 --> 00:13:14.372
seven months for melanoma. And virtually, no one lives past five years.

225
00:13:14.872 --> 00:13:18.352
But 20% lived past 10 just with a single agent trial with

226
00:13:18.392 --> 00:13:19.712
CTLA-4.

227
00:13:20.572 --> 00:13:23.592
But of course, what about the other 80%? Why didn't they respond?

228
00:13:23.632 --> 00:13:25.292
Well, I could give you some mechanistic

229
00:13:26.232 --> 00:13:29.952
interpretations, but the other explanations-- But the other possibility was there

230
00:13:29.972 --> 00:13:33.572
are other checkpoints. And sure enough, just about the time these results were

231
00:13:33.632 --> 00:13:37.542
coming in, Tasuku Hanjo, with the help of Gordon Freeman and

232
00:13:37.552 --> 00:13:41.072
Arlene Sharpe, showed that PD-1 was another checkpoint. But it's very different.

233
00:13:41.132 --> 00:13:44.812
It's expressed on exhausted cells, as I think everybody knows now,

234
00:13:45.052 --> 00:13:48.072
and gives rise to these precursor cells, the CD8s.

235
00:13:48.452 --> 00:13:52.222
So it acts on cells that have already been through differentiation and

236
00:13:52.452 --> 00:13:56.272
totally know their function. I'm bringing this up because it makes a

237
00:13:56.352 --> 00:13:59.772
big difference, as I'll show you in a moment, as to what they do and how they

